1
00:00:55,755 --> 00:00:58,883
There are some fish
that cannot be caught.

2
00:01:00,994 --> 00:01:04,020
It's not that they're faster
or stronger than other fish.

3
00:01:04,397 --> 00:01:07,491
They're just touched
by something extra.

4
00:01:08,768 --> 00:01:11,430
One such fish was The Beast.

5
00:01:13,039 --> 00:01:17,032
And by the time I was born
he was already a legend.

6
00:01:17,410 --> 00:01:21,847
He'd passed up more $ 100 lures
than any fish in Alabama.

7
00:01:23,616 --> 00:01:26,016
Some said that fish was
the ghost of a thief...

8
00:01:26,653 --> 00:01:29,486
...who'd drowned in that river
60 years before.

9
00:01:30,957 --> 00:01:35,656
Others claimed he was a dinosaur
left over from the "Cruaceous" Period.

10
00:01:35,829 --> 00:01:39,663
I didn't put any stock into
such speculation or superstition.

11
00:01:39,833 --> 00:01:42,563
All I knew was I'd been trying
to catch that fish...

12
00:01:42,735 --> 00:01:45,295
...since I was a boy
no bigger than you.

13
00:01:45,805 --> 00:01:48,296
And on the day you were born...

14
00:01:48,475 --> 00:01:51,410
Well, that was the day
I finally caught him.

15
00:01:54,013 --> 00:01:54,980
Now, I'd tried everything on it:

16
00:01:55,348 --> 00:01:58,977
Worms, lures, peanut butter,
peanut butter and cheese.

17
00:01:59,352 --> 00:02:01,786
But on that day I had a revelation:

18
00:02:01,988 --> 00:02:06,789
If that fish was Henry Walls' ghost,
then the usual bait wasn't gonna work.

19
00:02:06,993 --> 00:02:11,623
I was gonna have to use something
he truly desired.

20
00:02:12,365 --> 00:02:14,833
- Your finger?
- Gold.

21
00:02:15,735 --> 00:02:18,898
Now, I tied my ring onto
the strongest line they made...

22
00:02:19,072 --> 00:02:23,907
...strong enough to hold up a bridge,
they said, if only for a few minutes.

23
00:02:24,511 --> 00:02:27,105
And then I cast upriver.

24
00:02:29,983 --> 00:02:34,613
The Beast jumped up and grabbed it
before it even hit the water.

25
00:02:34,821 --> 00:02:39,349
And just as fast,
he snapped clean through that line.

26
00:02:39,492 --> 00:02:41,016
Well, you can see my predicament.

27
00:02:41,394 --> 00:02:45,353
My wedding ring,
the symbol of fidelity to my wife...

28
00:02:45,565 --> 00:02:48,090
...soon to be mother of my child...
- Make him stop.

29
00:02:48,735 --> 00:02:51,135
...was now lost in the gut
of an uncatchable fish.

30
00:02:51,671 --> 00:02:53,002
What did you do?

31
00:02:53,406 --> 00:02:56,569
I followed that fish upriver
and downriver.

32
00:02:58,411 --> 00:03:00,675
This fish, The Beast...

33
00:03:00,880 --> 00:03:06,785
...the whole time we were calling it
a him, when in fact it was a her.

34
00:03:06,986 --> 00:03:09,386
It was fat with eggs
it was gonna lay any day.

35
00:03:09,556 --> 00:03:12,047
Now, I was in a situation.

36
00:03:12,425 --> 00:03:15,883
I could gut that fish
and get my wedding ring back...

37
00:03:16,629 --> 00:03:21,566
...but in doing so I'd be killing the
smartest catfish in the Ashton River.

38
00:03:21,634 --> 00:03:23,932
Did I want to deprive
my son the chance...

39
00:03:24,103 --> 00:03:27,095
...to catch a fish like this
of his own?

40
00:03:28,107 --> 00:03:29,938
This ladyfish and I...

41
00:03:30,109 --> 00:03:34,637
- Well, we had the same destiny.
- "We were part of the same equation."

42
00:03:35,782 --> 00:03:37,807
Now, you may well ask...

43
00:03:38,017 --> 00:03:41,748
Oh, darling, darling,
it's still your night.

44
00:03:41,921 --> 00:03:47,791
...why did it strike so quick on gold
when nothing else would attract it?

45
00:03:47,961 --> 00:03:51,021
That was the lesson
I learned that day...

46
00:03:51,231 --> 00:03:54,200
...the day my son was born.

47
00:03:54,567 --> 00:04:00,563
Sometimes the only way to catch
an uncatchable woman...

48
00:04:00,773 --> 00:04:04,174
...is to offer her a wedding ring.

49
00:04:12,719 --> 00:04:15,449
What, a father's not allowed
to talk about his son?

50
00:04:15,622 --> 00:04:17,453
I'm a footnote in that story, Dad...

51
00:04:17,624 --> 00:04:23,688
...the context for your great adventure,
which never happened, incidentally.

52
00:04:23,763 --> 00:04:26,823
You were selling novelty products
in Wichita when I was born.

53
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:29,628
Come on, Will.
Everyone loves that story!

54
00:04:29,802 --> 00:04:34,068
They don't. I don't love that story. Not
anymore. Not after a thousand times!

55
00:04:34,274 --> 00:04:38,176
I know every punch line, Dad.
I can tell them as well as you can!

56
00:04:39,178 --> 00:04:41,738
For one night,
one night in your entire life...

57
00:04:41,914 --> 00:04:44,974
...the universe did not revolve
around Edward Bloom.

58
00:04:45,151 --> 00:04:49,645
- How can you not understand that?
- I'm sorry to embarrass you.

59
00:04:49,722 --> 00:04:53,590
You're embarrassing yourself, Dad.
You just don't see it.

60
00:04:55,728 --> 00:04:59,721
After that night, I didn't speak
to my father again for three years.

61
00:05:05,204 --> 00:05:09,163
William Bloom, United Press
International. If I could just...

62
00:05:13,012 --> 00:05:15,742
We communicated indirectly, I guess.

63
00:05:15,815 --> 00:05:19,751
In her letters and Christmas cards,
my mother wrote for both of them.

64
00:05:20,053 --> 00:05:24,956
And when I'd call, she'd say Dad was
out driving or swimming in the pool.

65
00:05:25,158 --> 00:05:28,127
True to form, we never
talked about not talking.

66
00:05:31,197 --> 00:05:34,894
The truth is, I didn't see anything
of myself in my father.

67
00:05:35,068 --> 00:05:38,299
And I don't think he saw anything
of himself in me.

68
00:05:41,974 --> 00:05:46,104
We were like strangers
who knew each other very well.

69
00:05:50,750 --> 00:05:52,980
In telling the story
of my father's life...

70
00:05:53,186 --> 00:05:57,714
...it's impossible to separate fact
from fiction, the man from the myth.

71
00:06:01,260 --> 00:06:04,252
The best I can do
is to tell it the way he told me.

72
00:06:06,065 --> 00:06:09,796
It doesn't always make sense,
and most of it never happened.

73
00:06:35,228 --> 00:06:37,196
Give me back my ring!

74
00:06:50,243 --> 00:06:51,141
Thank you!

75
00:06:51,644 --> 00:06:54,738
But that's what kind of story this is.

76
00:07:03,823 --> 00:07:07,020
His birth would set the pace
for his unlikely life.

77
00:07:07,193 --> 00:07:10,185
No longer than most men's,
but larger.

78
00:07:10,363 --> 00:07:12,797
And as strange as his stories got...

79
00:07:12,965 --> 00:07:16,366
...the endings were always
the most surprising of all.

80
00:07:43,162 --> 00:07:45,926
Yes. Yes, he's here.

81
00:07:47,066 --> 00:07:48,863
It's your mother.

82
00:07:55,875 --> 00:07:58,275
And what does Dr. Bennett say?

83
00:08:00,046 --> 00:08:01,911
No, sure, I'll talk to him.

84
00:08:02,982 --> 00:08:04,916
Yeah, I'll wait.

85
00:08:05,117 --> 00:08:06,675
It's bad?

86
00:08:06,853 --> 00:08:10,880
Yeah, it's more than they thought.
They're gonna stop chemo.

87
00:08:12,091 --> 00:08:14,787
- You need to go.
- Probably tonight.

88
00:08:16,062 --> 00:08:19,122
- I'm going with you.
- No, no, no. You shouldn't.

89
00:08:19,332 --> 00:08:21,129
I'm going with you.

90
00:08:50,396 --> 00:08:52,227
Now, which one's it gonna be?

91
00:08:52,398 --> 00:08:55,265
"Monkey in a Barn,"
or "Dog in the Road"?

92
00:08:55,401 --> 00:08:56,060
The one about the witch.

93
00:08:56,135 --> 00:08:57,500
The one about the witch.

94
00:08:57,770 --> 00:08:58,065
[Skipped item nr. 94]

95
00:08:58,137 --> 00:09:01,072
Your momma says I can't
tell you that one anymore.

96
00:09:01,140 --> 00:09:04,769
- You get nightmares.
- But I'm not scared.

97
00:09:06,412 --> 00:09:08,972
Well, neither was I, at first.

98
00:09:09,448 --> 00:09:12,349
Now, this took place
in the swamp outside of Ashton.

99
00:09:12,518 --> 00:09:17,182
Children weren't allowed in the swamp
on account of the snakes, spiders...

100
00:09:17,390 --> 00:09:22,020
...and quicksand that would swallow
you up before you could even scream.

101
00:09:22,228 --> 00:09:24,355
There were five of us
out there that night:

102
00:09:25,097 --> 00:09:28,362
Me, Ruthie, Wilbur Freely...

103
00:09:28,568 --> 00:09:32,231
...and the Price Brothers,
Don and Zacky.

104
00:09:32,438 --> 00:09:36,238
And not one of us knew
what was in store.

105
00:09:36,943 --> 00:09:41,039
It's common knowledge that most
towns of a certain size have a witch...

106
00:09:41,247 --> 00:09:43,374
...if only to eat
misbehaving children...

107
00:09:43,549 --> 00:09:46,985
...and the occasional puppy
who wanders into her yard.

108
00:09:47,053 --> 00:09:50,113
Witches use those bones
to cast spells and curses...

109
00:09:50,289 --> 00:09:52,780
...and make the land infertile.

110
00:09:52,959 --> 00:09:57,020
- Is it true she got a glass eye?
- I heard she got it from gypsies.

111
00:09:57,196 --> 00:09:59,323
- What's a gypsy?
- Your momma's a gypsy.

112
00:09:59,498 --> 00:10:00,897
Your momma's a bitch.

113
00:10:01,067 --> 00:10:03,228
You shouldn't swear.
There's ladies present.

114
00:10:03,402 --> 00:10:04,562
- Shit.
- Damn.

115
00:10:05,438 --> 00:10:05,904
Screw.

116
00:10:06,105 --> 00:10:08,130
Turn off your flashlights.
She'll see you!

117
00:10:08,307 --> 00:10:10,969
Yet of all the witches in Alabama...

118
00:10:11,143 --> 00:10:14,044
...there was one who was said
to be the most feared.

119
00:10:14,213 --> 00:10:18,240
For she had one glass eye which
was said to contain mystical powers.

120
00:10:18,451 --> 00:10:22,285
I heard if you look right at it,
you'll see how you're gonna die.

121
00:10:22,488 --> 00:10:26,185
That's bull-S-H-l-T, that is.
She's not even a real witch.

122
00:10:26,359 --> 00:10:28,384
If you're so sure, go get that eye.

123
00:10:28,561 --> 00:10:33,191
I heard she keeps it in a box on her
night table. Or are you too scared?

124
00:10:33,366 --> 00:10:35,493
I'll go in right now and get that eye.

125
00:10:35,868 --> 00:10:37,995
- Then do it.
- Fine, I will.

126
00:10:38,070 --> 00:10:40,971
- Fine, you do it.
- Fine, I'm doing it.

127
00:10:41,173 --> 00:10:43,334
Edward, don't!

128
00:10:43,509 --> 00:10:47,445
She'll make soap out of you.
That's what she does.

129
00:10:47,613 --> 00:10:50,275
She makes soap out of people.

130
00:11:40,199 --> 00:11:42,429
Ma'am, my name is Edward Bloom...

131
00:11:42,601 --> 00:11:45,263
...and there's some folks
like to see your eye.

132
00:11:58,451 --> 00:12:00,385
- You get The Eye?
- I brought it.

133
00:12:00,586 --> 00:12:01,644
Let's see it.

134
00:12:07,393 --> 00:12:09,258
Whoa, help!

135
00:12:19,205 --> 00:12:23,369
I saw how I was gonna die.
I was old and I fell.

136
00:12:24,210 --> 00:12:26,542
I wasn't old at all.

137
00:12:34,320 --> 00:12:37,585
I was thinking about death and all.
About seeing how you're gonna die.

138
00:12:37,990 --> 00:12:41,323
I mean, on one hand,
if dying was all you thought about...

139
00:12:41,627 --> 00:12:43,356
...it could kind of screw you up.

140
00:12:43,529 --> 00:12:47,260
But it could kind of help you,
couldn't it?

141
00:12:47,466 --> 00:12:51,493
Because, everything else,
you'd know you could survive.

142
00:12:54,373 --> 00:12:57,399
I guess I'm saying I'd like to know.

143
00:13:09,155 --> 00:13:11,146
That's how I go.

144
00:13:33,512 --> 00:13:34,570
Hi, Mom.

145
00:13:40,653 --> 00:13:45,716
- Is that Dr. Bennett's car?
- Yes. He's up with your father now.

146
00:13:46,225 --> 00:13:49,592
- And how is he?
- Well... No, I got it.

147
00:13:49,795 --> 00:13:53,788
He's impossible. He won't eat.
Because he doesn't eat, he's weaker.

148
00:13:54,166 --> 00:13:56,191
Because he's weak,
he doesn't want to eat.

149
00:13:56,368 --> 00:14:01,237
- How much time does he have left?
- You don't talk about that.

150
00:14:01,540 --> 00:14:04,031
Not yet.

151
00:14:04,710 --> 00:14:06,268
Will.

152
00:14:07,379 --> 00:14:10,348
Dr. Bennett. Oh, it's good to see you.

153
00:14:10,549 --> 00:14:13,814
My wife, Josephine.

154
00:14:14,086 --> 00:14:15,314
A pleasure.

155
00:14:16,689 --> 00:14:19,624
- You're seven months.
- To the day!

156
00:14:21,660 --> 00:14:22,820
It's a boy.

157
00:14:25,664 --> 00:14:31,296
Try to get him to drink one of these.
He won't, but go ahead and try.

158
00:15:17,283 --> 00:15:18,443
Dad?

159
00:15:19,251 --> 00:15:29,752
[Skipped item nr. 159]

160
00:15:29,828 --> 00:15:32,228
You want some water?

161
00:15:48,747 --> 00:15:52,683
- You are in for a surprise.
- Am I?

162
00:15:52,952 --> 00:15:55,750
Having a kid changes everything.

163
00:15:55,955 --> 00:15:59,721
There's the diapers and the burping
and the midnight feeding.

164
00:15:59,892 --> 00:16:02,861
- Did you do any of that?
- No.

165
00:16:03,595 --> 00:16:05,563
But I hear it's terrible.

166
00:16:06,198 --> 00:16:11,363
Then you spend years trying
to corrupt and mislead this child...

167
00:16:11,437 --> 00:16:16,465
...fill its head with nonsense,
and still it turns out perfectly fine.

168
00:16:16,675 --> 00:16:21,305
- You think I'm up for it?
- You learned from the best.

169
00:16:25,551 --> 00:16:27,951
Drink half the can.
I'll tell Mom you drank it all.

170
00:16:28,320 --> 00:16:29,753
Everyone wins.

171
00:16:30,389 --> 00:16:34,291
People needn't worry so much.
It's not my time yet.

172
00:16:34,460 --> 00:16:36,394
This is not how I go.

173
00:16:36,562 --> 00:16:40,692
- Really?
- Truly. I saw it in The Eye.

174
00:16:41,400 --> 00:16:44,665
- The old lady by the swamp?
- She was a witch.

175
00:16:44,870 --> 00:16:47,532
No, she was old and probably senile.

176
00:16:47,706 --> 00:16:52,803
I saw my death in that eye,
and this isn't how it happens.

177
00:16:53,012 --> 00:16:55,207
So how does it happen?

178
00:16:55,381 --> 00:16:59,784
Surprise ending.
Wouldn't want to ruin it for you.

179
00:17:00,986 --> 00:17:03,819
Your mother thought
we wouldn't talk again.

180
00:17:04,023 --> 00:17:06,821
Look at us. We're talking fine.

181
00:17:06,992 --> 00:17:08,823
We're storytellers, both of us.

182
00:17:09,028 --> 00:17:14,557
I speak mine out,
you write yours down. Same thing.

183
00:17:15,968 --> 00:17:17,629
Dad...

184
00:17:20,506 --> 00:17:22,974
I hope to talk about some things
while I'm here.

185
00:17:23,876 --> 00:17:25,468
You mean while I'm here.

186
00:17:25,911 --> 00:17:29,642
I just want to know
the true versions of things:

187
00:17:29,815 --> 00:17:32,613
Events. Stories.

188
00:17:32,918 --> 00:17:34,249
You.

189
00:17:45,864 --> 00:17:48,492
Your mother hasn't been
keeping up the pool.

190
00:17:48,667 --> 00:17:52,501
- lf you wanted to, you could fix it.
- Yeah, I will.

191
00:17:52,571 --> 00:17:55,699
- You know where the chemicals are?
- I did it when you were gone.

192
00:17:55,908 --> 00:18:01,847
I was never much for being
at home, Will. Too confining.

193
00:18:02,514 --> 00:18:05,039
And this here, being stuck in bed...

194
00:18:05,451 --> 00:18:08,818
Dying is the worst thing
that's ever happened to me.

195
00:18:09,788 --> 00:18:15,488
- I thought you said you weren't dying.
- I said this isn't how I go.

196
00:18:15,661 --> 00:18:19,563
The last part is much more unusual.

197
00:18:19,731 --> 00:18:21,961
Trust me on that.

198
00:18:54,933 --> 00:18:57,868
Dr. Bennett said I have
to stay at home for a week.

199
00:18:58,036 --> 00:19:01,733
Oh, that's nothing. Once,
I had to stay in bed for three years.

200
00:19:01,940 --> 00:19:05,103
- Did you have the chickenpox?
- I wish.

201
00:19:24,730 --> 00:19:27,460
Truth is, no one quite knew
what was wrong.

202
00:19:27,766 --> 00:19:30,132
Most times a person
grows up gradually...

203
00:19:30,502 --> 00:19:32,766
...while I found myself in a hurry.

204
00:19:36,008 --> 00:19:40,104
My muscles and my bones couldn't
keep up with my body's ambition.

205
00:19:40,746 --> 00:19:43,772
So I spent the better part
of three years confined to my bed...

206
00:19:43,982 --> 00:19:47,884
...with the encyclopedia being
my only means of exploration.

207
00:19:48,053 --> 00:19:50,021
I had made it all the way to the G's...

208
00:19:50,422 --> 00:19:53,084
...hoping to find an answer
to my "gigantificationism"...

209
00:19:54,026 --> 00:19:57,086
...when I uncovered an article
about the common goldfish.

210
00:19:57,763 --> 00:20:01,164
"Kept in a small bowl,
the goldfish will remain small.

211
00:20:01,533 --> 00:20:02,761
With more space...

212
00:20:02,935 --> 00:20:06,769
...the fish will grow double, triple,
or quadruple its size."

213
00:20:06,939 --> 00:20:10,136
It occurred to me then that perhaps
the reason for my growth...

214
00:20:10,776 --> 00:20:12,869
...was that I was intended
for larger things.

215
00:20:13,078 --> 00:20:16,639
After all, a giant man can't have
an ordinary-sized life.

216
00:20:18,150 --> 00:20:21,517
As soon as my bones had settled
in their adult configuration...

217
00:20:21,687 --> 00:20:26,624
...I set upon my plan to make
a bigger place for myself in Ashton.

218
00:20:26,692 --> 00:20:27,852
Tigers, go!

219
00:20:43,475 --> 00:20:45,033
Edward Bloom!

220
00:21:27,919 --> 00:21:31,912
Doggy! My doggy!
My doggy's trapped!

221
00:21:41,133 --> 00:21:44,125
I was the biggest thing
Ashton had ever seen.

222
00:21:45,003 --> 00:21:47,972
Until one day, a stranger arrived.

223
00:22:03,221 --> 00:22:07,885
Calm down. Calm down, everybody.
Calm down. That's enough.

224
00:22:08,060 --> 00:22:11,826
- Mr. Mayor, he ate an entire corn field.
- He ate my dog.

225
00:22:12,030 --> 00:22:14,624
If you ain't gonna stop him, mayor,
we will.

226
00:22:14,833 --> 00:22:17,825
I won't have mob violence
in this town.

227
00:22:18,036 --> 00:22:19,936
Now, has someone tried
talking to him?

228
00:22:20,105 --> 00:22:22,767
- You can't reason with him.
- He's a monster.

229
00:22:23,041 --> 00:22:24,736
I'll do it.

230
00:22:39,358 --> 00:22:41,758
I'll talk to him.
See if I can get him to go.

231
00:22:41,927 --> 00:22:44,225
That creature could crush you
without trying.

232
00:22:44,596 --> 00:22:47,565
Oh, trust me, he'll have to try.

233
00:23:18,997 --> 00:23:20,362
Hello?

234
00:23:25,237 --> 00:23:28,035
My name is Edward Bloom,
and I wanna talk to you!

