beside him...

475
00:47:44,528 --> 00:47:46,689
...he blocked out the daylight!

476
00:47:47,497 --> 00:47:51,490
Not to alarm you, ma'am,
but if this man wanted to...

477
00:47:51,702 --> 00:47:56,196
...he could crush your head
between his toes...

478
00:47:56,373 --> 00:47:59,809
...like a tiny walnut.
But he won't do it.

479
00:48:00,444 --> 00:48:02,571
No. No, ladies and gentlemen...

480
00:48:02,746 --> 00:48:04,805
...he will not hurt her...

481
00:48:05,282 --> 00:48:08,718
...because he is our own gentle giant.

482
00:48:10,220 --> 00:48:16,318
Ladies and gentlemen,
I give you Colossus!

483
00:49:40,811 --> 00:49:44,474
Ladies and gentlemen,
boys and girls...

484
00:49:44,648 --> 00:49:46,946
...thank y'all for coming.

485
00:49:47,818 --> 00:49:50,719
Drive home safely, everyone.
Thank you for coming.

486
00:49:51,321 --> 00:49:54,848
It was on that night
Karl met his destiny.

487
00:49:55,826 --> 00:49:58,590
And I met mine, almost.

488
00:49:58,762 --> 00:50:03,597
They say when you meet
the love of your life, time stops.

489
00:50:03,767 --> 00:50:05,291
And that's true.

490
00:50:50,514 --> 00:50:53,574
What they don't tell you
is that once time starts again...

491
00:50:54,384 --> 00:50:58,013
...it moves extra fast to catch up.

492
00:51:30,921 --> 00:51:32,388
What's your name?

493
00:51:33,657 --> 00:51:37,559
- It's Karl.
- Karl.

494
00:51:42,999 --> 00:51:48,562
Tell me, Karl, have you ever heard
the term "involuntary servitude"?

495
00:51:48,772 --> 00:51:51,605
- No.
- "Unconscionable contract"?

496
00:51:53,777 --> 00:51:56,644
- Nope.
- Great.

497
00:51:56,813 --> 00:51:58,838
Here you go.

498
00:51:59,983 --> 00:52:01,712
Here you are.

499
00:52:04,955 --> 00:52:07,719
Mr. Soggybottom,
come down this here...

500
00:52:07,891 --> 00:52:10,086
...so he can use your back
to sign on it.

501
00:52:22,973 --> 00:52:25,100
Okay. Thank you. Yeah.

502
00:52:26,576 --> 00:52:28,476
Hey, kid.

503
00:52:28,645 --> 00:52:31,944
- Your friend just made himself a star.
- Oh, that's great.

504
00:52:34,818 --> 00:52:36,911
- My attorney, Mr. Soggybottom.
- Good to meet you.

505
00:52:37,087 --> 00:52:38,748
Pleased to meet you.

506
00:52:43,894 --> 00:52:46,920
What's the matter? I haven't
seen a customer so depressed...

507
00:52:47,130 --> 00:52:50,463
...since the elephant sat
on that farmer's wife.

508
00:52:51,701 --> 00:52:53,794
"Depressed"?

509
00:52:55,505 --> 00:52:57,837
See? The big guy likes it.

510
00:52:58,708 --> 00:53:00,733
I just saw the woman I'm gonna marry.

511
00:53:00,911 --> 00:53:03,971
I know it. But I lost her.

512
00:53:05,115 --> 00:53:06,514
Oh, tough break.

513
00:53:06,683 --> 00:53:10,551
Well, most men have to get married
before they lose their wives.

514
00:53:10,720 --> 00:53:15,783
I'm gonna spend the rest of my life
looking for her. That or die alone.

515
00:53:16,126 --> 00:53:17,991
Damn, kid.

516
00:53:21,198 --> 00:53:23,666
Let me guess. Real pretty?

517
00:53:24,935 --> 00:53:26,800
Reddish-blondish hair?

518
00:53:28,638 --> 00:53:29,900
Blue dress?

519
00:53:31,441 --> 00:53:32,931
Yeah!

520
00:53:33,109 --> 00:53:36,078
I know her uncle. Friends of the family.

521
00:53:36,446 --> 00:53:38,607
Who is she? Where does she live?

522
00:53:38,682 --> 00:53:41,515
Forget it. Don't waste your time.
She's out of your league.

523
00:53:41,685 --> 00:53:45,052
- What? You don't even know me.
- Sure I do.

524
00:53:45,222 --> 00:53:49,750
You were hot shit back in Hickville, but
here in the real world, you got squat.

525
00:53:49,926 --> 00:53:51,860
You don't have a plan or a job.

526
00:53:52,028 --> 00:53:54,519
Nothing except the clothes
on your back.

527
00:53:54,965 --> 00:53:57,866
Well, I have a whole backpack
full of clothes.

528
00:53:59,002 --> 00:54:01,766
Oh, someone stole my backpack.

529
00:54:02,606 --> 00:54:06,542
You were a big fish in a small pond,
but this here is the ocean...

530
00:54:06,743 --> 00:54:09,177
...and you're drowning.
Go back to Puddleville.

531
00:54:09,813 --> 00:54:12,839
- You'll be happy there.
- You say I don't have a plan. I do.

532
00:54:13,016 --> 00:54:16,645
I'll find that girl, marry her,
and spend the rest of my life with her.

533
00:54:17,120 --> 00:54:20,851
I don't have a job, but I would
have a job if you gave me one.

534
00:54:21,057 --> 00:54:23,025
And I may not have much...

535
00:54:23,226 --> 00:54:26,923
...but I have more determination
than any man you're likely to meet.

536
00:54:29,165 --> 00:54:32,828
I'm sorry, kid. I don't do charity.
Come on, big boy.

537
00:54:33,870 --> 00:54:36,168
Wait. Look, I'll work
night and day for you...

538
00:54:36,940 --> 00:54:38,100
...and you won't have to pay me.

539
00:54:40,143 --> 00:54:43,112
You just have to tell me who she is.

540
00:54:46,750 --> 00:54:48,718
Every month you work for me...

541
00:54:48,918 --> 00:54:52,217
...l'll tell you one thing about her.
That's my final offer.

542
00:54:56,192 --> 00:54:58,752
Let's get started.

543
00:55:12,142 --> 00:55:15,805
From that moment on, I did everything
Mr. Calloway asked.

544
00:55:15,879 --> 00:55:18,780
I'd go three days
without stopping to eat.

545
00:55:18,982 --> 00:55:21,610
And four days without sleeping.

546
00:55:21,818 --> 00:55:24,651
What kept me going was
the promise of meeting the girl...

547
00:55:24,821 --> 00:55:26,015
...who would be my wife.

548
00:55:33,830 --> 00:55:36,128
Stick together, that's the way
it's gonna be.

549
00:55:36,333 --> 00:55:40,201
- The way it was, and the way it will be.
- Mr. Calloway, sir?

550
00:55:40,570 --> 00:55:42,128
It's been a month today.

551
00:55:44,140 --> 00:55:47,268
This girl, the love of your life...

552
00:55:48,178 --> 00:55:52,740
...her favorite flowers are daffodils.

553
00:55:53,917 --> 00:55:57,876
- So get that stuff...
- Daffodils.

554
00:55:58,688 --> 00:56:00,986
Daffodils.

555
00:56:02,692 --> 00:56:04,853
Daffodils.

556
00:56:10,967 --> 00:56:12,594
True to his word...

557
00:56:12,736 --> 00:56:15,330
...every month Amos would tell me
something new...

558
00:56:15,705 --> 00:56:17,969
...about the woman of my dreams.

559
00:56:18,141 --> 00:56:21,042
Enjoy yourselves, enjoy yourselves.

560
00:56:21,211 --> 00:56:22,769
She's going to college.

561
00:56:23,146 --> 00:56:27,344
College. She's going to college.

562
00:56:37,994 --> 00:56:39,359
She likes music.

563
00:56:40,130 --> 00:56:43,896
Music. She likes music.

564
00:56:48,171 --> 00:56:50,196
Over the months, I learned a lot
about the woman I would marry...

565
00:56:50,273 --> 00:56:52,901
Over the months, I learned a lot
about the woman I would marry...

566
00:56:52,976 --> 00:56:56,070
...but not her name,
and not where to find her.

567
00:56:56,146 --> 00:57:00,879
That time had come.
I couldn't wait any longer.

568
00:57:12,162 --> 00:57:14,357
Mr. Calloway?

569
00:57:16,433 --> 00:57:19,834
It's Edward Bloom.
I need to talk to you.

570
00:57:24,107 --> 00:57:26,405
Mr. Calloway?

571
00:58:00,276 --> 00:58:01,971
No. Wait!

572
00:58:19,829 --> 00:58:24,289
That night, I discovered that most
things you consider evil or wicked...

573
00:58:24,501 --> 00:58:28,369
...are simply lonely and lacking
in social niceties.

574
00:59:02,906 --> 00:59:04,965
Didn't kill anything, did I?

575
00:59:05,975 --> 00:59:10,309
A few rabbits. But I think one of them
was already dead.

576
00:59:13,550 --> 00:59:16,519
That would explain the indigestion.

577
00:59:24,093 --> 00:59:25,993
Thank you.

578
00:59:28,097 --> 00:59:29,928
I was wrong about you, kid.

579
00:59:30,099 --> 00:59:33,398
You may not have much,
but what you got, you got a lot of.

580
00:59:33,903 --> 00:59:36,235
You could get any girl.

581
00:59:36,406 --> 00:59:38,374
There's only one I want.

582
00:59:43,179 --> 00:59:44,407
Her name...

583
00:59:47,917 --> 00:59:50,010
...is Sandra Templeton.

584
00:59:52,121 --> 00:59:55,056
She goes to Auburn.

585
00:59:55,224 --> 00:59:59,456
Semester's almost over,
so you better hurry.

586
00:59:59,829 --> 01:00:01,353
Thank you. Thank you.

587
01:00:02,065 --> 01:00:04,465
- Good luck, kid!
- Thank you, sir!

588
01:00:17,113 --> 01:00:17,477
- Bye, now.
- Bye, Edward.

589
01:00:21,117 --> 01:00:24,416
After saying my goodbyes,
I hopped three trains...

590
01:00:24,587 --> 01:00:28,045
...to get to Auburn that afternoon.

591
01:01:03,226 --> 01:01:07,060
You don't know me,
but my name is Edward Bloom...

592
01:01:07,130 --> 01:01:08,392
...and I love you.

593
01:01:10,333 --> 01:01:14,064
I've spent the last three years
working to find out who you are.

594
01:01:14,237 --> 01:01:18,435
I've been shot, stabbed, and trampled
a few times. I broke my ribs twice.

595
01:01:19,042 --> 01:01:22,034
But it's all been worth it
to see you here now...

596
01:01:22,211 --> 01:01:25,146
...and to finally get to talk to you.

597
01:01:25,348 --> 01:01:27,612
Because I'm destined to marry you.

598
01:01:28,518 --> 01:01:34,457
I knew it when I saw you at the circus,
and I know it now more than ever.

599
01:01:36,125 --> 01:01:39,424
- I'm sorry.
- You don't have to apologize to me.

600
01:01:39,595 --> 01:01:41,995
I'm the luckiest person
you'll find today.

601
01:01:42,198 --> 01:01:45,258
No, I'm sorry I'm engaged
to be married.

602
01:01:52,442 --> 01:01:55,536
But you're wrong. I do know you.

603
01:01:55,712 --> 01:01:57,680
At least by reputation.

604
01:01:58,648 --> 01:02:01,116
Edward Bloom from Ashton.

605
01:02:01,584 --> 01:02:06,021
See, I'm actually engaged
to a boy from Ashton. Don Price.

606
01:02:06,656 --> 01:02:09,216
He was a few years older than you.

